{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_biotite_ver01/data/sn89051220/00513688556/1921032401/0466.xml":{"full_text":"PARIS\nFORTY-SECOND YEAR\nPARIS. ARKANSAS, THURSDAY, MARCH 24. 1921\nNUMBER 4\nGOVERNOR M\u2019RAE DEFERS\nTHE PENALTY ON TAXES\nThe following proclamation deferr\ning the penalty on taxes has been\nissued by Governor McRae:\n\u201cI, Thomas C. McRae, governor\nof the state of Arkansas, believing\nthat it will be helpful to many tax\npayers, and not hurtful to the state,\ncounties, municipal and school dis\ntricts, by virtue of the authority in\nme vested, do hereby proclaim, re\nquest and direct (1) that, the tax\ncollectors of the several counties in\nthis state shall not collect from the\npersons, firms and corporations who\nowe county, municipal, state and\nschool taxes the 10 per centum pen\nalty authorized by Section 10066 of\nCrawford Moses\u2019 Digest; (2) nor\nshall they collect from such persons,\nfirms and corporations who may owe\nsuch taxes the 25 per centum pen\nalty that shall be assessed by the\ncounty clerks against lands and lots\nreturned as delinquent for the non\npayment of taxes thereon under\nSection 10083 of Crawford Moses\u2019\nDigest of the Statutes of Arkansas,\nif the taxes and costs are paid on or\nbefore the day provided by law for\nthe delinquent tax sale,.\n\u201cThe purpose of this proclamation\nis not to extend the time for the\npayment of taxes, nor to prevent\nthe final collection of the penalties\n.for the non-payment thereof, nor to i\ninterfere with the advertisement'and\nsale of property for the non-pay\nment of taxes, costs and penalties,\nas provided by ,la^, but is only to\nextend the time for the assessment\nand collection of all the penalties\ndenounced by law for the non-pay\nment of the county, municipal, state\nand school taxes, until the day fixed\nby law for the sale of lands returned\nas delinquent;and I hereby proclaim,\nrequest and direct that if all the\nsaid taxes and costs due on any\ntract of land or lot shall not be\npaid on or before the day fixed by\nlaw the same shall be sold for the\npayment of ftie taxes, cost and pec\nally, as if this proclamation had not\nbeen issued.\n\u201cDone at my office in the city of\nLittle Rock, Ark., this March 18th,\n1921.\n(Signed) \u201cT. C. McRae.\u201d\nHome Demonstration Notes\n[M. F. Mitchell, County Agent]\nCare of Day-Old Chicks\nChicks should have some sand or\nfine chick grit for the first feed.\nFrom the very first try and have\nbuttermilk or sour milk before them.\n_ But be sure it is sour. It .often\npays to dip the bill of each chick in\nbuttermilk or sour milk. They will\nsoon learn to like it and it will pre\nvent bowel trouble.\nDry rolled oats are a first good\nfeed. Give them just the amount\nthey will clean up in about fifteen\nminutes and feed at least five times\na day. Crumble up bits of the\nrolled oats and scatter it in the\nclpver chaff that is recommended for\nchicks, or any other litter, that you\n^rnay have. This Induces tfje chicks?\nfrom the first to exercise. Some\nfew years ago we fed mashes to\nchicks on shingles or plates and they\nobtained what they wanted to eat\nbut did not have the exercise. We\nnow feed dry feeds more and more\nand place it in the.slitter so the\nchick early in^life learns to scratch.\nCorn bread well baked is a good\nfeed. If you have been successful\nwith' some special brand of chick\nfeed just keep on feeding the same.\nRemember that scratching ia na\nture\u2019s method of exercising the\nchicks, and if they linger around\nthe feed hopper at all times and\ncram with mash and take little ex\nercise, it increases the danger of;\ndigestive disorders.\nThe water for the chicks should'\nnot be ice cold. It pays to take off\nthe chill, and I believe that our Best\npoultry men aie beginning to be\nlieve that cold water is the cause of\nbowel trouble to a great degree\nwhen given at an early age. One\nvery successful poultry woman I\nhave known personally, boiled every\ndrop of water she fed ti her little\nchicks for four weeks. She loses\nvery few chicks Let the supply of\nwater alway be fresh and very\nclean. Do not let the chicks \u201cwa\u2019\nlow\u201d in the drinking water.\nToe punch your chicks.\nMay Suggest Pact Against Japanese\nParis. Rene Vivian!, former pre\nmier of Prance, who sailed for the\nUnited States recently, is carrying to\nWashington a proposal for a Franco\nAmerican alliance against Japan, ac\ncording to information which was re\nceived from a personage who is in a\nposition Nto know the purpose of the\nmission and to-enjoy its confidence.\nFrance\u2019s proposed alliance is not\nframed as a pistol pointed at Japan\u2019s\nheart, exactly, but it will be drafted\nmore as an agreement between the\ntwo republics to maintain a status quo\nin the Far East and in the Pacific.\nThe French colony in Indo-China\n\u00abtn4 America\u2019s open-door policy will\nserve as the raison de\u2019etre for linking\nthe two republics\u2019 interests in the\nOrient.\nWuai D\u2019Orsay is confident that a\nFranco-American alliance in the Far\nEast would result systematically in a\nFranco-American protective alliance\nagainst Germany, It is not expected\nthat the military alliance drafted by\nformer President Wilson and Clemen\nceau in 1919 will be accepted by the\nRepublicans or by the Senate, but it is\nbelieved that a French offer of aid\nagainst Japan might become retroac\ntive and insure France of America\u2019s\nsupport in case of future German ag\ngression.\nCertain official circles in France\niissert that the United States neither\nseeks nor needs an ally for a possible\nconflict with Japan, but it is generally\nbelieved that, owing to the Anglo-Jap\nanese treaty, Washington would not be\nadverse to having a friend in Europe.\nThe French diplomats are divided\ninto two groups, one advocating an\nalliance with Great Britain and the\nother insistent on France\u2019s emanicipa\ntion from England\u2019s domination, is\ndemanding that Quai D\u2019Orsay exert ev\nery effort to furmulate an alliance\nwith the United States. Clemenceau\nand his followers are leaders of the\nAnglophile faction, together with a\nconsiderable portion of the military\nhelorarchy.\nThe anglophiles base their beliefs\non the fact that thev United States\nArmy has been pared down to an in\nsignificant force, preparedness appar\nently has been abandoned by America,\nand the supremacy of the English\nfleet, but chiefly because of the near\nness of France and England to each\nother.\nWill Stop Ginning April 1\nTo Our Customers:\nThose who have cotton picked and\nstored, if you want it ginned this\nseason,' will please bring it to the\ngin before April 1, as we will close\nfor the season on that date.\n3-2 v Mashaw Conley.\nMethodist Bazarr\nThe ladies of the Methodist church\nwill hold a bazarr and sell dressed\nhens, cakes and candy at L. P; Ja\ncobs\u2019 hardware store, March 26th.\nGet your name on the honor roll.\nMules are Cheaper\ni.r\n'i\nikf\na *1\n*;\u00a7*\u2019!.1\nI I\nTwo hundred head of\nHorses, Mares and\nMules for sale\nCASH OR TIME\n\u25a0~.y V,.\nSEE\n444 LEON A. WILLIAMS 444\nFORT SMim ARK.\n____Jl\n;i I**\nCABINET WOULD\nBOOST BUSINESS\nWashington. How to boost Amer\nican business at home and abroad\nwas the principal subject of discus\nsion at a recent meeting of President\nHarding with his cabinet\nThe president took an optimistic\n\u25bclew of the present period of business\ndepression. He reported to his offi\ncial advisers the substanoe of the\nbaits he has had in the last few days\nwith the heads of great Industrie*;\nlike James A. rarren, of the United\nStates Steel Corporation.\nInformation which has come to the\npresident in this way is that the\nlow tide of business depression has\nbeen passed and that conditions are\nbeginning to improve in those indus\ntries, particularly those which 'have\nbeen hit by the buying slump and\nfaill in prices.\nMr. Harding directed the cabinet\ndiscussion to the consideration of def\ninite policies for fostering the expan\nsion of domestic and foreign com\nmerce, which he sums up as the pro\nmotion of national prosperity, one of\nthe highest functions of government.\nThe president indicated that he fa\nvors the abolition of fettering. re\nstrictions imposed on industrial and\nagricultural development and a great\ned degree of co-operation between\nthe government and the business ac\ntivities of the country.\nIn the field of foreign commerce\nthe president cited the fact that the\nlack, of government co-operation and\noutright restrictions had served to\nplace American business at a 'disad\nvantage in competing with foreigners\nwhose governmtents are extremely\npaternalistic in the promotion of\nforeign. trade. Such foreign paternal\nism takes the form of government\nsubsidies of ship lines and the ext^p\nI sion of banking and marketing facili\nI ties to exporters.\nWhile not advocating direct subsi\ndies to American ship lines, the\npresident was of the opinion that\nAmerican ships should be relieved of\nthe payment of Panama canal tolls\nI and that the government should fur\nnish the same aid to exporters en\nl ojyed by their foreign competitors.\nSecretary of Commerce Hoover ex\npressed the opinion that one of the\nfirst steps taken should be the amend\nment of the Webb-Pomerene act,\nwhich permits combination of export\ners, so as to enable them to operate\ndistributing agencies abroad* He also\ndescribed his plan fcff advisory com\nj mittees of the principal industries of\nthe country which will co-operate\nwith the government in developing\nthe production and marketing of the\nsort of goods required by foreign cus\ntomers. He will formulate this plan\nat a meeting with a committee of the\nChamb'er of Commerce of the United\nStates in the near future.\nCaillaux In Riot.\nGrenoble,' France.\u2014Many persons!\nwere injured in rioting here ouslde a\ntheater where Joseph Caillaux, form\ner premier, was delivering a lecture\nunder auspices of the Socialist muni\ncipality andthe League for the Rights\nof Man. M. Caillaux was freed in\n1920 after having been sentenced to\nseveral years\u2019 imprisonment for his\n\u201cdefeatist\u201d policy during the war.\nBank Closes Doors.\nBeaver, Pa.\u2014The First National\nBank of Beaver has closed its doors.\nFred Wilson, vice president, said that\nan examination of the hank\u2019s books\ndisclosed an irregularity, and the\nbank was closed for an investigation\nand to protect interests of the stock\nholders.\nRate Argument Ends.\nWashington. Arguments in the\nWisconsin rate case, described by\nsome participating attorneys as the\n\u201cmost important states\u2019 rights issue\nbefore the Supreme Court in many\nyears,\u2019\u2019 has been closed.\nWill Reduce Wages.\nPhiladelphia. The Pennsylvania\nRailroad announced it will post no\ntices informing all officers and em\nployes that it proposes to reduce sal\naries and wages, effective April 20.\nEndorsed for Postmasters\nAt a meeting of the Republican\nCounty Central Committee at Paris\nMonday, the following named were\nendorsed for appointment as post\nmasters for their respective towns\nParis, Herman Hixson.\nScranton, R. B. Chitwood.\nBooneville, J. L. Callahan.\u201d\nMagazine, E. S. Berry.\nBeer andi&oot Beer on Draught\nIt looks like the real beer. It\ntastes like the real beer, and of\ncourse it is an ice cold and refresh\ning drink. See U3 when dry we\nhave the thing.- 3tf\nJoe Girard Son\u2019s Confectionery.,\nThe Paris Express -and Commer\ncial Appeal ^1.251\nBRUNO CONFIDENT\nGERMANS CAN PAY\nParis.\u2014The allied reparations com\nmission, in its note to Germany de\nmanding fulfillment of article 235 of\nthe peace treaty, notified the Ger\nman government it must pay one bil\nlion gold marks before March 23, it\nwas announced. The money must be\ndeposited in the Bank of France,\nBank of England or the Federal Re\n\u2022ervo Bank in the United States, Ger\nmany was told.\nIt must complete the payment of\n20,000,000,0<>0 gold marks by May 1.\nThe commission gave Germany un\ntil April l to submit a proposal to\npay the balance of the 20,000,000,000\nmarks otherwise than in cash,\ni Germany may submit a plan for a\nforeign loan by April 1 with the pro\nt ceeds of which shall be payable to\nthe commission. The commission an\ni nounced that Germany had virtually\ns refused to pay the balance, asserting\nthe 20,000,000,000 marks had been ful\ndy paid.\nPremier Briand, replying to inter\npellations In the Chamber of Depu\nties regarding the London reparations\nconference, said that if the allies re\nmain firm and united the Germans\nwill discover that they (the Germans)\nhave astonishing resources. Germany\nhad been vanquished, he declared,\nbut, unfortunately, psychologically\nthis was insufficiently aj^arent to the\nGerman people.\nM. Briand told the Chamber he\nwent to the London conference bound\nto maintain the reparations figures\narrived at in Paris, but ready to make\ni concessions regarding the methods of\npayment.\nI \u201cI frankly told our allies there was\nj a wall against which we were back\nJed,\u201d he declared.\nt Crossing Crash Fatal.\nCuero, Tex. Mts. D. B. Frils was\ninstantly killed and her husband, D.\nB. Frils was probably fatally injured\nwhen their automobile was struck by\na Southern Pacific train, three miles\nleast ot Cuero. Their son, Willie, es\n\"eaped.\nWill Sign Trade Pact.\nLondon.\u2014The Anglo-Russian trade\nagreement will be signed. Negotia\ntions between Leonid Krassin, the\nRussian representative, and the Board\nof Trade have resulted in reframing\nsome of the clauses in a manner ac\nceptable to the British government.\nTo Clean >JJp St. Louis.\nSt. Louis.\u2014A force of about 30 fed\neral prohibition enforcement agents,\nsorn^ from New York and some from\nArkansas,are here for the purpose, it\nwas announced, of \u2018\u201ccleaning up\u2019\u2019 St.\nLouis.\nWill Visit Mexico.\nNew Orleans.\u2014Acting on a formal\nInvitation from President Obregon, 80\nNew Orleans business men have left\nfor Brownsville, Tex., where they\nwill cross into Mexico for a trade ex\ntension trip of 17 days.\nAmerican Ship Missing.\nLondon. The American freight\nsteamer Hewitt, which left Sabine\nJanuary 20 for Boston, has been post\ned as missing. The steamer which\nhas a normal crew of 54, has a gross\ntonnage of 5,398.\nTo Consider Wage Cut.\nAtlanta, Ga.\u2014The Nashville, Chat\ntanooga and St. Louis railroad has\nannounced that it had requested a\nconference of representatives of its\nunskilled laborers in Nashville to\npropos^a wage reduction.\nPremier\u2019s Slayer Held.\nMadrid.\u2014Anatenoto Pedro Mateo,\nan anarchist, was arrested and, ac\ncording to the police, confessed to\nthe assassination of Premier Dato.\nHe gave the names of alleged accom\nplices.\nWithdrawal Not Asked.\nManagua, Nicaragua. The Sen\nate has rejected a motion to request\nthe United States to withdraw the\nAmerican troops stationed in\nManagua.\nExtension Notes\nIt is usually difficult to realize\nthat often blessings come to us in\ndisguise. In some respects the pres\nent condition of affairs will prove\nto be a blessing in disguise. One of\nthe favorable signs, I think, is the\nearnestness manifested in farmers\u2019\norganizations. Some of these organ\nizations are taking steps looking to\nfuture betterment if carried out.\nAt Blaine and Delaware polato\ngrowers are organizing and getting\nready to enter the potato business\nin a business way. Those who are\ngoing into the busine s should fol\nlow the \u2018\u2018Safe Farming\u201d schedule\nand not become so interested in this\nj>ne commodity that shoJi'TtT the msr\niket fail to offer a prn\u00a3 the grower\nI iJ\nwould be almost ruined. The amount\nof sweet potatoes being consumed is\nincreasing year by year but there is\nsuch a thing as getting so many\npotatoes on the market that there\nwill not be a profit to the grower.\nThen, too, the grower should be\nsure of a curing house. Produce a\ndisease free crop of nice smooth po\ntatoes. well cured and graded and\nif there is a market they will com\nmand the top price!\nThis is a year when special stress\nshould be placed on soil building.\nThere is not very flattering pros\npects for any extra profit on any\ncrop, so if we are going to work\nwithout a profit why not let the\nwork gb into the improvement of\nthe soii.\nYour county agent will attend the\nmarketing meeting at Little Rock\nTuesday. The object of this meet-!\ning is to work out a marketing sys\ntem for cotton, sweet potatoes and\nrice\u2014three of the money crop* of\nArkansas.\nFollowing this meeting the coun\nty agents of the state will have a\nmeeting for two days, laying out j\nplans for the year.\nDon\u2019t forget peas, soy beans and\npeanuts.\nM.C.Ferguson,\nCounty Agent.\nHeld to Grand Jury\nThe- cases of Vernon and Virgil\nSmith and Clarence Kimberling, who j\nare charged with the murder of\nLouis Butzer near Corley, March 10,\nwere given their preliminary hear\ning before Justice C. E. Gray Mon\nday and were bound over to await\nthe action of the grand jury.\nThe defendants were arraigned\nbefore Esq. Z. S. Walker Wednes\nday of last week and a continuance\nwas granted until Saturday morn\ning, and at that time a change of\nvenue was taken to Justice Gray\u2019s\ncourt and the case set for trial Mon\nday. v\nIt is conservatively estimated that\nthe largest crowd ever attending a\npreliminary hearing in the history\nof Logan county assembled at the\ncourt house Saturday, only tq be\ndisappointed when the case was con\ntinued.\nJustice Gray convened court Mon\nday morning, and due to the large\nnumber of witnesses the taking of\ntestimony was not completed until\nabout 10:30 that night. The coun\nsel for the defense, Attorneys W.\nB. Rhyne and Robt. J. White, and\nProsecuting Attorney Thos. H. Rog\ners for the state, presented their ar\nguments, and Justice Gray decreed\nthat the defendants should be held\nwithout bail to await the action of\nthe grand jury.\n-_____\nLone Gnm School House, March 25th\nThere will be a 5-act play given\nat Lone Gum school house Friday\nnight, March 25, entitled \u201cTony the\nConvict.\u201d Admission 15 and 25c.\nProceeds go for the benefit of the\nschool. Everybody cordially invited\nto come and help in a good cause.\nCommittee.\nParis Express and Kansas City\nStar $1.25.\n\u201cBOLSHEVISM IN RUSSIA,\u201d\nWINGO DELIVERS ADDRESS\n\u201cHow Bolshevism Ruined Russia,\u2019*\nan illustrated address, was given at\nthe court house Sunday night by\nRev. Chas. Franklin. This address\nwas the fifth of a series on \u201cBetter\nAmerica\u201d prepared by Dr. Newell\nDwight Hillis, and was of especial\ninterest. The history of Russia in.\nher struggle for a democratic form\nof government was vividly portrayed\nby word and picture, and the chaos\nof that country wrought under the\nleadership of bolshevists is sufficient\nto convince all liberty-loving people\nthat Russia is not advancing to the\ngoal of a government of and by the\npeople, but that the bolshevists have\ndestroyed what little advance that\nwas made in that direction and this\ngreat country is now in the midst of.\nthe worst reign of terror in history.\nThe addresses are well worth\nwhile, being of an educational value\nand instill into the hearts of our.\ncitizenship a greater love of country\nand home.\nAt the close of Rev. Franklin a\nremarks, Congressman Otis Wingo\nwas introduced and made a short\naddress, along the lines brought out\nin the illustrated lecture. Mr.\nWingo very eloquently and convinc\ningly told of the conditions as they\nexist in Russia today, gaining much\nof his information from the Ameri\ncan ambassador to that country.\nHis review of that people\u2019s effort to\nestablish a government patterned\nafter our own, of the progress made,\nand of the overthrow by the bol\nshevists of what had been accom\nplished, added much weight to the\npreceeding address.\nMr. Wingo explained the differ\nence in the bolshevist form of gov\nernment and our own, especially ap\npealing to the children, so that they\nmight more fully appreciate the ad\nvantages and liberties accorded to\nthe citizens of on rjjountr-y.~ iffie- a'.~p-.\nso warned his hearers of the menace\nof bolshevism in this country, but\nadded that he believed in the conti\nnuity of our government and that it\nwould be the rich heritage of gen\nerations yet unborn.\nMr. Wingo has been in congress\nfor a number of years, and keeps in\nclose touch with his constituency.\nHis visits over the district are for\nthe sole purpose of ascertaining\nwhat the people want, and also for\nlending them any assistance possible.\nHis long tenure in office has not\nlessened bis desire to be a \u201cservant\nof the. people,\u201d but rather has it in\ncreased his desire and bin capacity\nfor service. Every person in his\ndistrict, from the richest to the\npoorest, regardless of political pref\nerence, always commands a respect\nful hearing from Mr.Wingo, and he\nhas made it an unfaltering rule to\nanswer every letter received.\nWhen all our public officials so\nlearn the lesson of service due the\npeople, an insurmountable obstruc\ntion will be placed in the pathway\nof bolshevism in its endeavor to\noverthrow our government.\nTHE UNIVERSAL CAR\nWILL C. GREENWOOD\nParis, Arkansas\nThe Ford Model T One Ton Truck was the\nfirst low price truck to carry the worm-drive\u2014\nthat tremendous power delivering mechanism\nhad previously been an exclusive feature with\nhigh priced motor trucks. In the Ford Truck,\nhowever, you get the worm-drive of manganese\nbronze material, absolute in strength and\npositive in the delivery of power, at a very low\nprice. Come in and let us point out the many\nsuperior merits of the. Ford One Ton Truck,\nbecause you need 'one ftf ybor work. We give\nprompt and efficient repair service.\u00bb-.\n\n_l_CkyA&vm","height":"26112","width":"18700"}}
